  abstract = {Patterns in soil N supply in 5 ecosystems in the Noatak National Preserve in Alaska, USA were examined and the potential response of N availability to changes in soil moisture and temperature was studied using 15N pool-dilution techniques. In-field N availability was estimated using ion exchange resin bags and incubation of soil cores in plastic bags. Nitrogen availability was highest in an ecosystem dominated by Alnus crispa and lowest in ecosystems dominated by willows (Salix) or cotton grass tussocks. Repeated watering increased net N mineralization rates by 1.5-3 fold. Net N mineralization at 12 deg C was 5-10 fold greater than at 5 deg C. The interaction between water and temperature was nonsignificant for both net nitrification and net mineralization with the exception of a tundra site. The results suggested that moderate (5 deg C) increases in soil temperature should be expected to substantially increase soil N availability in the short term. Longer term responses may depend on dynamics of litter input and feedback responses within plant and microbial communities.},
