  volume = {72},
  issn = {0099-2240},
  abstract = {The intramolecular distribution of nitrogen isotopes in N2 O is an emerging tool for defining the relative importance of microbial sources of this greenhouse gas. The application of intramolecular isotopic distribu- tions to evaluate the origins of N2 O, however, requires a foundation in laboratory experiments in which individual production pathways can be isolated. Here we evaluate the site preferences of N2 O produced during hydroxylamine oxidation by ammonia oxidizers and by a methanotroph, ammonia oxidation by a nitrifier, nitrite reduction during nitrifier denitrification, and nitrate and nitrite reduction by denitrifiers. The site preferences produced during hydroxylamine oxidation were 33.5 ? 1.2\textperthousand, 32.5 ? 0.6\textperthousand, and 35.6 ? 1.4\textperthousand{} for Nitrosomonas europaea, Nitrosospira multiformis, and Methylosinus trichosporium, respectively, indicating similar site preferences for methane and ammonia oxidizers. The site preference of N2 O from ammonia oxidation by N. europaea (31.4 ? 4.2\textperthousand{}) was similar to that produced during hydroxylamine oxidation (33.5 ? 1.2\textperthousand{}) and distinct from that produced during nitrifier denitrification by N. multiformis (0.1 ? 1.7\textperthousand{}), indicating that isotopomers differentiate between nitrification and nitrifier denitrification. The site preferences of N2 O pro- duced during nitrite reduction by the denitrifiers Pseudomonas chlororaphis and Pseudomonas aureofaciens (?0.6 ? 1.9\textperthousand{} and ?0.5 ? 1.9\textperthousand, respectively) were similar to those during nitrate reduction (?0.5 ? 1.9\textperthousand{} and ?0.5 ? 0.6\textperthousand, respectively), indicating no influence of either substrate on site preference. Site preferences of ?33\textperthousand{} and ?0\textperthousand{} are characteristic of nitrification and denitrification, respectively, and provide a basis to quantitatively apportion N2 O.},
